HEADWORD: Epithalamium
<hw>Ep`i*tha*la"mi*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Epithalamiums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L.
<plw>Epithalamia</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/ , orig.
an adj., nuptial; <grk>'epi`</grk> upon, at + <?/ bride chamber.]</ety>
<def>A nuptial song, or poem in honor of the bride and
bridegroom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The kind of poem which was called <qex>epithalamium</qex> . . .
sung when the bride was led into her chamber.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epithalamy</ent>⟦br⟧
